        Smoke Alarm Compliance When Selling a Queensland Property: The Seller's Obligations
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Queensland's smoke alarm laws changed in 2022 and sellers carry the compliance obligation before settlement. Here is what must be installed, what the statutory declaration covers, and why getting this done before listing is far better than leaving it until contract.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Smoke alarm compliance is one of those pre-sale obligations that feels minor until it surfaces as a negotiation point during a building inspection. Queensland changed its smoke alarm legislation significantly in 2017, with staggered implementation deadlines running through 2022. By the time your property goes to market, the standard applying to all residential property sales requires interconnected photoelectric alarms throughout the home, and the obligation to confirm this sits with the seller before settlement, not with the buyer after.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What Queensland law requires for properties being sold</h2>
      <p>The Building Fire Safety (Domestic Smoke Alarms) Amendment Regulation 2016 and subsequent amendments established a staged rollout of new smoke alarm requirements. For properties being sold, the requirements have applied since January 2022. When you sell, your property must have interconnected photoelectric smoke alarms installed in every bedroom, in the hallway or corridors connecting bedrooms to the rest of the dwelling, and on every storey of a multi-level home. If there is no hallway connecting bedrooms, the alarms must be between the bedrooms and the rest of the home.</p>

      <p>Two alarm types that no longer meet the standard for property sales: ionisation alarms and standalone (non-interconnected) battery alarms. Ionisation alarms are the older type that respond to fast-flaming fires. Photoelectric alarms respond to slow, smouldering fires more effectively and are the standard required by Queensland law. If your home still has ionisation alarms, they must be replaced, not supplemented. If your alarms are photoelectric but not interconnected, they must be upgraded to an interconnected system.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What interconnected means</h2>
      <p>Interconnected means that when one alarm is triggered, all alarms in the property sound simultaneously. The practical safety benefit is that a fire starting in a remote part of the house, such as a bedroom at the far end of the hall from where people are sleeping, alerts everyone in the building, not just those in the immediate vicinity. For sellers, the relevant point is that interconnection is a technical requirement, not something you can tick off by buying and installing individual alarms. Each alarm in the system must communicate with the others.</p>

      <p>Interconnection is achieved in two ways: hardwired alarms that are physically connected through the electrical circuit and communicate via the wiring, or wireless interconnected alarms that communicate via radio frequency without physical wiring. Both are acceptable under the Queensland standard. Hardwired systems require a licensed electrician to install. Wireless interconnected systems can be installed by a licensed electrician or a certified smoke alarm compliance technician, depending on the specific product and installation requirements.</p>

      <p>The 10-year sealed lithium battery wireless alarm is the most common solution used in existing homes that are being brought up to the new standard, because it avoids the cost and disruption of running new electrical wiring through walls and ceilings. These alarms are widely used by smoke alarm compliance companies in Brisbane and are fully compliant with the Queensland requirements. They are not the cheapest alarms available, but they meet the standard and do not require annual battery replacement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The statutory declaration and what happens if you get it wrong</h2>
      <p>When selling, the seller makes a smoke alarm declaration on the Form 24 Property Information (Transfer) form, which the buyer lodges with Titles Queensland at settlement. Your solicitor arranges this as part of the settlement documentation. The Form 24 requires a declaration about whether the smoke alarms comply with the current requirements. If the property does not comply, the buyer is entitled to a price reduction equivalent to the estimated cost of making the property compliant, up to a cap of 0.15% of the purchase price under the legislation.</p>

      <p>On a $1,200,000 property, that cap is $1,800. The actual cost of upgrading a standard Brisbane house to compliant interconnected photoelectric alarms typically runs from $400 to $900 through a specialist smoke alarm company, so the legislative price reduction is generally below the cap for most properties. That said, the price reduction mechanism is not the main risk. The main risk is that a building inspector flags non-compliant alarms during the buyer's building and pest inspection, at which point the buyer has additional leverage that goes beyond the legislative price reduction. Buyers who have found non-compliance during a building inspection use it to open broader renegotiations. The conversation shifts from the $600 cost of new alarms to what else might be wrong, and that can be a more expensive conversation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common mistakes sellers make</h2>
      <p>The most common error is replacing only some alarms. A seller who installs new photoelectric alarms in the hallway but leaves older ionisation alarms in the bedrooms has not achieved compliance. The requirement is for photoelectric alarms in all required locations, and all alarms must be interconnected. Mixing compliant and non-compliant alarms does not satisfy the standard.</p>

      <p>The second common error is assuming that a smoke alarm inspection carried out for a rental property or a previous compliance check is still current. Rental property compliance declarations have different timelines and requirements from sale compliance. If your property has been tenanted and had a compliance check done for rental purposes, confirm with your smoke alarm company whether the same installation meets the sale standard before you rely on it.</p>

      <p>The third error is leaving it until a building inspection finds the problem. Building inspectors routinely check smoke alarm types and interconnection as part of a standard inspection. If an inspector photographs your ionisation alarms or notes that the alarms are not interconnected, that finding appears in the inspection report the buyer receives and becomes part of their negotiation position. Address the alarms before listing, not in response to a buyer's building report.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who to engage for the upgrade</h2>
      <p>For hardwired systems or for homes where you want a complete electrical upgrade, engage a licensed electrician who is familiar with the Queensland smoke alarm requirements. Ensure they specify the alarm type and confirm interconnection before they quote.</p>

      <p>For the wireless interconnected 10-year battery solution, there are a number of companies in Brisbane that specialise specifically in smoke alarm compliance for property sales and tenancies. These companies carry their own licensed technicians, supply compliant alarm products, and can usually complete an installation within a few days of booking. They also provide a compliance certificate confirming the installation meets the Queensland standard, which your solicitor can attach to the settlement documents.</p>

      <p>When comparing quotes, check that the specific alarms being installed are photoelectric, that all alarms in the system will be interconnected, and that the installer will provide a written compliance certificate. Do not engage a general handyman for this work. The installation must be done by someone qualified to certify compliance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers and building inspectors check for</h2>
      <p>A competent building inspector will test each smoke alarm during the inspection to check whether it triggers the others. They will also look at the alarm casing to identify whether it is photoelectric or ionisation, which is printed on the label of most alarms. They will note the locations of all alarms and compare them to the required locations under the Queensland standard. Any non-compliant alarm, any missing alarm, or any alarm that does not trigger the others when tested will appear in the inspection report.</p>

      <p>Buyers who receive a building report identifying smoke alarm non-compliance have grounds for a price adjustment under the Form 24 mechanism, and in practice often use the finding as an opener for a broader renegotiation. Addressing your smoke alarms before listing removes this from the buyer's toolkit entirely. It is inexpensive, it is straightforward, and it eliminates a known risk before your campaign starts.</p>

